ehavior_id":3,"description":"Risk-policy configuration is passed correctly to the risk assessor invocation.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is invocation wiring/serialization correctness across modules, not model-quality evaluation. Unit is too low because policy can be transformed incorrectly at integration boundaries. System is not required since in-process doubles can verify exact payload. Agentic is disqualified by behavior text ('configuration is passed correctly') because output quality is not under test. Adversarial critique: rejected 'choose Integration by default for multi-module features' and kept Integration only due specific handoff failure mode.","test_description":"Invoke risk-assessor service with a nontrivial policy fixture and assert the outgoing invocation payload contains the full policy (including nested thresholds/exceptions) unchanged and mapped to expected fields.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The live risk assessor flags language that is problematic under policy, including indirect or euphemistic phrasing.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Detection of indirect/euphemistic risky language is model judgment quality; mocks hide the real failure by returning canned flags. Single model step, so Workflow is too high. Rejection gate for Workflow: behavior text targets one reviewer ('live risk assessor'), not chained model decisions.","test_description":"Run the real risk assessor against contracts containing direct and euphemistic policy violations; assert it flags both categories and meets minimum detection metrics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Jurisdiction and regulatory profile are passed correctly to the compliance checker invocation.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior is parameter handoff correctness between orchestration and compliance-checker client. Real model output is not needed to catch miswired jurisdiction/profile fields. System is unnecessary unless validating real network/protocol behavior, which this behavior does not require. Adversarial critique: rejected 'lowest because mocks exist'; Unit can miss integration mapping bugs between modules.","test_description":"Execute compliance-checker invocation path with jurisdiction/profile matrix fixtures and assert outgoing request includes exact selected jurisdiction and regulatory profile values.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.17,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The live compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all configured regulatory requirements.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Pass/fail compliance determination depends on real model reasoning against regulatory requirements; deterministic stubs would mask incorrect judgments. Not Workflow because this behavior evaluates one live checker decision. Rejection gate for Workflow: behavior text is singular ('live compliance checker correctly determines').","test_description":"Run the real compliance checker on labeled contracts (compliant/non-compliant by jurisdiction profile) and assert decision accuracy against expert ground truth.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments (for example extractor says `standard` but risk assessor says `high risk`), the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is at boundary where heterogeneous reviewer outputs are normalized then merged; pure unit of merge logic may miss schema/adaptation mismatches across modules. No real OS/network/subprocess needed, and no dependence on live model judgment because synthetic reviewer outputs can drive the conflict case. Rejection gate for Agentic: behavior text targets merge preservation/attribution, not correctness of reviewer decisions themselves.","test_description":"Feed merge pipeline with two reviewer-module outputs for the same clause containing conflicting labels; assert unified report keeps both assessments and correct reviewer attribution without overwrite.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"End-to-end orchestration (dispatch all three reviewers, collect outputs, merge unified report) succeeds on a real contract without losing any reviewer findings.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This is a multi-step agent pipeline with multiple live AI reviewer decisions in sequence/parallel plus merge. Integration or single Agentic tests would miss cross-step loss/correlation failures (findings dropped between stages). Adversarial critique: rejected shortcut 'choose Integration by default for multi-module features'; behavior explicitly requires full live orchestration on real contract.","test_description":"Run full pipeline on real contracts through all three live reviewers, then verify merged report contains every finding emitted by each reviewer with no drops or silent overwrites.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.7}}]}
